#Text=Gros Morne National Park
#Text=Gros Morne National Park is on the west coast of Newfoundland , Canada .
#Text=Understand
#Text=A UNESCO World Heritage site , Gros Morne National Park protects an area of impressive natural beauty , rural Newfoundland culture , and unique geological wonders .
#Text=The park 's namesake mountain , Gros Morne , is the second highest point in Newfoundland at 806 metres .
#Text=Its French meaning is " large mountain standing alone , " or more literally " great sombre . "
#Text=It covers an area of 1,805 km ² ( 697 sq mi ) .
#Text=Gros Morne is a member of the Long Range Mountains , an outlying range of the Appalachian Mountains , stretching the length of the island 's west coast .
#Text=It is the eroded remnants of a mountain range formed 1.2 billion years ago .
#Text=The park 's operating season is from mid-May to mid-October :
#Text=most facilities are open seven days a week , including holidays .
#Text=This is the high season , so you should book your accommodation well in advance .
#Text=The park is open in winter with some activities available in winter .
#Text=All major travel routes are maintained throughout the year , although temporary closures or warnings may come into effect in the event of adverse weather conditions .
#Text=Visitor Centre , Rocky Harbour , ☏ +1709 458-2417 , ✉ grosmorne.info@pc.gc.ca .
#Text=History
#Text=The Gros Morne National Park Reserve was established in 1973 and received UNESCO World Heritage Site status in 1987 .
#Text=It became a national park on October 1 , 2005 .
#Text=Landscape
#Text=The park is in the Long Range mountains , an extension of the Appalachian chain running up the west coast of the island of Newfoundland .
#Text=The landscape of the park is mountainous and rugged , and has a number of interesting geological features , including a number of fjords and the barren Tablelands .

#Text=The park 's rock formations include oceanic crust and mantle rock exposed by the obduction process of plate tectonics , as well as sedimentary rock formed during the Ordovician , Precambrian granite and Palaeozoic igneous rocks .
#Text=Tablelands
#Text=The Tablelands , found between the towns of Trout River and Woody Point in south west of Gros Morne National Park , look more like a barren desert than traditional Newfoundland .
#Text=This is due to the ultramafic rock — peridotite — which makes up the Tablelands .
#Text=It is thought to originate in the Earth 's mantle and was forced up from the depths during a plate collision several hundred million years ago .
#Text=Peridotite lacks some of the usual nutrients required to sustain most plant life and has a toxic quality , hence its barren appearance .
#Text=Peridotite is also high in iron , which accounts for its brownish colour ( rusted colour ) .
#Text=Underneath this weathered zone , the rock is really a dark green colour .
#Text=Fauna
#Text=The most notable animal in the park is the moose , part of a booming population that was introduced to Newfoundland around 1900 .
#Text=Other common wildlife in the park include an ecotype of caribou ( R. t caribou ) , black bears , red foxes , Arctic foxes , snowshoe hares , red squirrels , lynxes , river otters and beavers .
#Text=Harbour seals are common in St. Pauls inlet , and whales ( pilots minkes , humpbacks , fins ) may be in the area especially during the capelin season in early summer .
#Text=Many bird species can be found in the park , from shorebirds along the ocean to birds of the bogs and interior forests .
#Text=Climate
#Text=The climate in this part of Newfoundland is on the cool side of temperate - daytime highs are around 20°C in the summer and -5°C in the winter .
#Text=Annual precipitation is just over 1300 mm .
#Text=Get in

#Text=Most visitors to Gros Morne will probably either fly in to the airport at Deer Lake , about an hour away , and rent a car there ( a number of major rental companies have a presence ) , or take the ferry from North Sydney in Nova Scotia to Port aux Basques .
#Text=Reservations for the ferry are essential .
#Text=By plane
#Text=Deer Lake Regional Airport ( YDF ) , 1 Airport Road Suite 1 , Deer Lake ( 35 km from the southern park boundary . ) , ☏ +1709 635-3601 , ✉ info@deerlakeairport.com .
#Text=The airport is served by direct daily flights from Montreal ( May – October ) , Toronto , Halifax , and St. John ’s .
#Text=Intra-provincial flights are available between Deer Lake and St. John ’s .
#Text=There are bus services that can also provide transportation from the town of Deer Lake to Gros Morne .
#Text=By car & ferry
#Text=If driving from the Canadian mainland , the shortest way to Gros Morne is via the ferry service between North Sydney , Nova Scotia , and Port aux Basques , Newfoundland .
#Text=It is 300 km from Port aux Basques to the southern park boundary , about a four-hour drive .
#Text=Marine Atlantic , toll-free : +1-800-341-7981 ( reservations ) , ✉ customer_relations@marineatlantic.ca .
#Text=Ferries run year-round between North Sydney , Nova Scotia , and Port aux Basques on Newfoundland ’s southwest coast .
#Text=Ferry service between North Sydney and Argentia , on Newfoundland ’s east coast , is offered from mid-June to late September .
#Text=The crossing time from North Sydney to Port aux Basques is approximately 6 hours , and 11 hours from North Sydney to Argentia .
#Text=Reservations strongly recommended .
#Text=Labrador Marine .
#Text=Summer .
#Text=This ferry links northern Newfoundland with southern Labrador .
#Text=Fees and permits
#Text=These numbers were updated in 2018 .
#Text=Daily fees
#Text=May 16-Oct 31 .
#Text=Adults $ 9.80 , seniors $ 8.30 , families $ 19.60 , children under 18 free .
#Text=Nov 1-May 25 .
#Text=Adults $ 7.80 , seniors $ 6.80 , families $ 15.70 , children under 18 free .
#Text=Annual passes .
#Text=Adults $ 49.00 , seniors $ 41.70 , families $ 98.10 , children under 18 free .
#Text=Wilderness hiking fees .
#Text=Long range reservation fee $ 24.50 , Long Range hike $ 83.40 per person , North Rim hike $ 68.70 per person , combined Long Range and North Rim hike $ 122.60 per person .
#Text=Parks Canada Passes
#Text=The Discovery Pass provides unlimited admission for a full year at over 80 Parks Canada places that typically charge a daily entrance fee
#Text=It provides faster entry and is valid for 12 months from date of purchase .
#Text=Prices for 2018 ( taxes included ) :
#Text=Family/group ( up to 7 people in a vehicle ) : $ 136.40
#Text=Children and youth ( 0-17 ) : free
#Text=Senior ( 65+ ) : $ 57.90
#Text=The Cultural Access Pass : people who have received their Canadian citizenship in the past year can qualify for free entry to some sites .
#Text=Get around
#Text=A car is probably the most convenient way to get around , because the park is huge , and things are far apart .
#Text=Biking may also be an option , if you do n't mind lots of hills .
#Text=Be careful if you drive at night , since moose are often spotted on the roads in Newfoundland , and collisions are common .
#Text=An adult moose can weigh well over a ton , and hitting one at highway speeds is likely to be fatal .
#Text=Moose are most active around dawn and dusk , so be vigilant if you 're driving at those times .
#Text=Rocky Harbour ( Inside the park . ) , ☏ +1709 458-2376 , ✉ info@rockyharbour.ca .
#Text=This small town has accommodations , restaurants , shops and services , and is an excellent base for exploring the park .
